==English==
===Alternative forms===
* {{alter|en|ibent}}
===Etymology===
From {{inh|en|enm|ybende}}, {{m|enm|i-bente}}, from {{inh|en|ang|*ġebended}}, past participle of {{der|en|ang|bendan}} as well as {{m|ang|ġebendan}}. Equivalent to {{af|en|y-|bend|-t}}.
===Verb===
{{head|en|verb form}}
# {{term-label|en|obsolete}} {{past participle of|en|bend}}: [[bent]]
#* {{quote-book|en|year=1567 |title=Of the Tormets of Hell and the Paines of Loue|author=George Turbervile|page= |ISBN=|passage=Though Tytius doe indure his Liuer to be rent Of Vultures tyring on the same unto his spoyle '''ybent''':}}
#* {{RQ:Spenser Shepheardes Calender|chapter=December|folio=49|folioend=49|versoend=1|passage=And for I was in thilke ſame looſer yeares, / (Whether the Muſe, ſo wrought me from my birth, / Or I tomuch beleeued my ſhepherd peres) / Somedele '''ybent''' to ſong and muſicks mirth, / A good olde ſhephearde, ''Wrenock'' was his name, / Made me by arte more cunning in the ſame.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|year=1611 |title=The Troublesome Raigne of King Iohn |author=William Shakespeare|page= |ISBN=|passage=My boy shew me thy hand, blesse thee my boy, For in thy palme I see a many troubles are '''ybent''' to dwel, But thou shalt scape them all, and doe full well. }}
